<font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="4" color="#990000"><b>What else to read</b></font><p>
<font face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif" size="2">The best biography of Eugene Debs, <i><a href="http://www.haymarketbooks.org/Merchant2/merchant.mv?Screen=PROD&amp;Store_Code=Haymarket&amp;Product_Code=UHPTBC" target="_blank">The Bending Cross</a></i>, by Ray Ginger, was republished this year by Haymarket Books, with a new introduction by Mike Davis.<p>
For a book on the history of the Socialist Party and Debs' involvement in it, read <i><a href="http://www.haymarketbooks.org/Merchant2/merchant.mv?Screen=PROD&amp;Store_Code=Haymarket&amp;Product_Code=UHPASM" target="_blank">The American Socialist Movement</a></i>, by Ira Kipnis. Many Debs' speeches and writings, including the Canton antiwar speech, are collected in <i><a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/redirect.html?ie=UTF8&amp;location=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.amazon.com%2FEugene-V-Debs-Speaks%2Fdp%2F0873481321%3Fie%3DUTF8%26s%3Dbooks%26qid%3D1184528342%26sr%3D1-1&amp;tag=socialistwork-20&amp;linkCode=ur2&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325" target="_blank">Eugene V. Debs Speaks</a></i>.<p>
<i>SW </i>columnist Sharon Smith's <i><a href="http://www.haymarketbooks.org/Merchant2/merchant.mv?Screen=PROD&amp;Store_Code=Haymarket&amp;Product_Code=LMSF" target="_blank">Subterranean Fire: A History of Working Class Radicalism in the United States</a></i> is an excellent book on the hidden history of workers' resistance and the socialist tradition in the U.S.
